(48, 3, 14, 44, 2, 33, 33, 'promise of the Spirit through faith', 'Connection of the Holy Spirit', 'Both passages emphasize the promise of the Spirit. Galatians speaks of receiving the promise through faith, while Acts describes the outpouring of the Holy Ghost as a fulfillment of that promise.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(48, 3, 15, 58, 9, 17, 17, 'no man disannulleth, or addeth thereto', 'Covenant and Testament Relationship', 'This connection highlights the concept of a covenant or testament being unchangeable once established. Both passages emphasize the idea that a covenant or testament is valid only after certain conditions are met, specifically the death of the testator.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(48, 3, 15, 45, 6, 19, 19, 'no man disannulleth, or addeth thereto', 'Covenant and Servanthood Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of yielding and commitment in both passages. Galatians discusses the unchangeable nature of a covenant, while Romans emphasizes yielding one''s members to righteousness, suggesting a commitment to a new covenant of holiness.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(48, 3, 15, 45, 3, 5, 5, NULL, 'Human Reasoning in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize human reasoning in discussing divine matters. Galatians uses a human covenant analogy, while Romans presents a rhetorical question framed as human reasoning.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(48, 3, 15, 46, 15, 32, 32, NULL, 'Covenant and Human Experience', 'This connection highlights the human experience of struggle and the permanence of covenants. Both passages emphasize the significance of commitments and the consequences of actions in life and death.', 'theme', 0.3, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
