(48, 4, 27, 8, 4, 14, 16, 'Rejoice, thou barren that bearest not', 'Barren Woman and Restoration', 'This connection highlights the theme of restoration and joy in barrenness. In Galatians, the barren woman is called to rejoice, while in Ruth, Naomi experiences restoration through the birth of a child, emphasizing the joy that comes from unexpected blessings.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(48, 4, 27, 9, 2, 5, 5, NULL, 'Connection of Barren Women', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of barrenness leading to unexpected fruitfulness. In Galatians, the barren woman is celebrated for having many children, paralleling the message in 1 Samuel where the barren woman also bears seven children.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(48, 4, 27, 8, 1, 11, 13, 'barren that bearest not', 'Barren Women and Hope', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of barrenness and the hope for future offspring. In Galatians, the barren woman is encouraged to rejoice, while Naomi expresses her despair over her inability to bear children.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
